Configuration without hardcoding values using Jakarta EE Config in a Jakarta EE application.

- Create an interface for your configuration properties, such as `MyConfig.java`. This interface defines the properties you want to configure.

```
import org.eclipse.microprofile.config.inject.ConfigProperty;

public interface MyConfig {
    @ConfigProperty(name = &quot;my.property&quot;)
    String myProperty();
}
```

You can access your environmental variables like this below. check this [link](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-functions/functions-reference-java?tabs=bash%2Cconsumption#environment-variables).

![enter image description here](https://i.imgur.com/on8ZKcD.png)

- Create property files for each environment you want to support. For example, I have created two property files as `application-dev.properties` and `application-prod.properties`.

![enter image description here](https://i.imgur.com/K5hMOZ4.png)

Inject the configuration properties:

```java
import javax.inject.Inject;

public class MyService {
    @Inject
    private MyConfig myConfig;

    public String getMyProperty() {
        return myConfig.myProperty();
    }
}
```

Jakarta EE application can dynamically switch configurations by changing the environment-specific property files or by modifying the active profile.

