Java&#39;s proxies cannot extend a class, because they already extend `java.lang.reflect.Proxy`. They can only implement interfaces, so you&#39;ll never be able to get a `BigDecimal` instance, only a `Comparable`. If you need more capabilities, you have to look into ByteBuddy, CGLib (this is what Spring uses when it has to proxy concrete classes, but it&#39;s barely maintained these days) or similars libs, they can produce what you&#39;re after.

Here&#39;s one way to do it using ByteBuddy (note that I&#39;m not exactly familiar with ByteBuddy, so I may have done something wrong):

```java
public class Test {

    //No need to generate a new class for each proxy instance
    private static final Class&lt;? extends BigDecimal&gt; PROXY_TYPE = generateProxy();

    private static Class&lt;? extends BigDecimal&gt; generateProxy() {
        return new ByteBuddy()
                .subclass(BigDecimal.class)
                .method(ElementMatchers.isEquals())
                .intercept(MethodDelegation.to(Interceptor.class))
                .make()
                .load(Test.class.getClassLoader()) //BigDecimal classloader won&#39;t know where to find Interceptor.class
                .getLoaded();
    }

    public static class Interceptor {
        @RuntimeType
        public static boolean intercept(@This BigDecimal _this, @AllArguments Object[] args) throws Throwable {
            Object that = args[0];
            return that instanceof BigDecimal &amp;&amp; _this.compareTo((BigDecimal) that) == 0;
        }
    }

    public static BigDecimal getScaleObliviousProxy(BigDecimal scaleAwareBigDecimal) {
        try {
            return PROXY_TYPE.getConstructor(String.class).newInstance(scaleAwareBigDecimal.toString());
        } catch (ReflectiveOperationException e) {
            throw new RuntimeException(e);
        }
    }

    @Test
    public void testCustomBigDecimal() {
        BigDecimal ten = BigDecimal.TEN;
        BigDecimal x = getScaleObliviousProxy(new BigDecimal(&quot;10.0&quot;));
        assertTrue(x.equals(ten));
    }
}
```

